Date 1-7-62

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 02/21/2013 10:42 AM

1 962

At the office this morning.

A final check on the paper "The Folklore Treatment of Snake Bite".

Delivered this at noon at a meeting of the Aardvarks Ltd. A very fancy lunch, of which, unfortunately, I could partake to only a small degree, since I have found that it's quite upsetting (and actually painful) to talk on a full stomach. There were about 60 present and the speech seemed to go over OK. The men are mostly those who enjoy a fancy (and expensive) meal.

In the evening I talked to the Fellows of the Natural History Society on "Delayed Book Review" = Plinly. There were about 125 present. It seemed to be appreciated and went quite smoothly. Phil, Larry, GG, Bapse present.

Notes:

pamg

1 962

At the office this morning. Talked with Noble about a right-of-way problem.

Caught the 12:50 train for Los Angeles. First went to the Metropolitan Coach Depot at 6th & Main and got a time table for buses to Fullerton.

At the Public Library 4:30 to 5:30. They didn't have the Nevada Directory by Gillis. Got out the Electrical World for Nov 23, 1918 and looked up the article I had published on the line losses chargeable against a second block of power.

Caught the Lark for San Francisco.
__________________________________________________
January 19th (Continued)

Murray. I then went to the U. C. Press. Fruge was in New York and I saw no one else that I knew. Caught the bus back to SF but got soaked, even though I had on overcoat and hat. I was very cold and wet. Called Dorie. She had no family news to report.

Notes:

pamg

Date 1-18-62

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 02/21/2013 07:36 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 01:05 PM

1 962

Arrived in San Francisco on time (8:30). Went up to the Fairmont. Called Abajian at the California Historical Society and inquired about the Gillis Directory. They didn't have it.

Went to the meeting of directors of the California State Chamber of Commerce from 10 to 2, including lunch. Then road over to the Sather Gate of the University of California in Norman Sutherland's car. Went to the Bancroft Library and found they had the Gillis Nevada Directory (1808-69). Looked in vain for father's name, as well as Mandlebaum's in all the towns including Carson and Genoa. There were no entries of any kind either personal or commercial. This was from 2:30 to 3:40. This was a disappointment as I had hoped to clear up the details of father's career from 1863 to 1869, when he came to San Diego. I had other things to clear up but was so tired that I quit. It was now raining cats 'n dogs. I called on Stebbins for a short time but then some visitors came in on appointment and I had to leave. He promised to check with Keith
_____________________________________________________
(Continued on Jan 18th)

Notes:

pamg

Date 1-19-62

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 02/21/2013 07:45 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 01:05 PM

1 962

This morning I had expected to take a taxi from Glendale and catch the 9 o'clock bus to Fullerton So I could attend the second Annual Informal Get Together of the Southern California Herpetologists. But the train was 3/4 hour late and it was still raining so I decided to forgo the Fullerton meeting. I would have missed all but the lunch, and I wasn't feeling too hot.

Got home at 1:30 and spent the afternoon catching up.

Went to Scholia in the evening. Graydon Hoffman talked on City government, particularly the Council-City Manger form. When it came time for my discussion I practically lost my voice. My vocal cords seem shot.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 02/21/2013 07:51 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 01:05 PM

1 962

Miscellaneous catch up today.

1 962

At the office this morning. Warren Larude of the AP called and we discussed a possible news release on the AP wire for a Sunday feature on my folklore care as given before the Aardvarks. This was 10-10:25. I loaned him by speech.

Chris Parrish called this afternoon to study the king-snake skin he had found in Angel de la Guarda Island. Fortunately I had saved it and it was still in good condition. I showed him a lot of King snake data sheets.

Lerude called twice tonight to check certain items.

1962

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 02/23/2013 03:15 PM

1 962

Finished checking the first draft of 1961 income tax report. All that is required now is copying.

Wrote some letters.

Marguerite and Lucy from La Mesa here for lunch.

Went to a fine concert by Artus Rubenstein tonight. We had a narrow escape on the way to the concert when a car coming fast and running the wrong way on a one-way cross street just missed the rear of Shorty's Chev station wagon. The street was partly closed because of the freeway construction. As the man was driving the wrong way on a one-way street , there was no stop sign at first street. By a violent wrench of his wheel he missed the rear of our car by about a foot. Had he hit us broadside it would have been a very serious situation.

Notes:

1962

Finished the Forward poem.

Went to the Stanford Conference at Catamaran Hotel 11:45-4:30. Heard "The Care and Feeding of Six Billion People" by Weldon B. Gibson; and "National and International Communism" by Wayne D. Vucinich.

Tonight at Scholia, gave the Pliny talk. Took 40 minutes (without the discussion period). Think it went ok; the questions and comments showed this. The lighting was poor so that I occasionally fumbled in reading. Must watch this in future. Present were Bloomenshine, Borchers, Brown, Cohn, Grant, Haines, Hall, Hoffman, Janssen, Leonard, Lindsay, Schroeder,& Tidwell; also Fletcher amd Barnes.

Got up this morning at 3 and worked until 5:30 on the Cerritos talk. Then continued from 8:30 until noon. I'm not sure that I have improved on the original Salt Lake City talk. Maybe I try too hard. Worked on it again until 3; part is to be read -- this is new, and part to be ad libbed from notes.

Started for Norwalk and Cerritos College at 4. Had some little difficulty finding the place from Loomis's map, as it was farther from the Freeway than the map made it seem. Anyway arrived on time -- 6:30.

Loomis met us, and thereafter we met or renewed acquaintance with a lot of people--too many to remember, but I do recall Jay Savage, Bilderback, James Peters, Brattstrom, et al.

The talk went OK -- they seemed to like it and laughed at the gags. I talked for 65 minutes and they stood up and clapped. There were about 100 present. This was the annual meeting of the Southern California Academy of Science.

(June 29, Continued)
where we saw the Ukranianian Dance Company from Kiev. This was very fine, exceedingly agile dancers, great precision, colorful costumes, and altogether a very rewarding performance. The house was full and the audience enthusiastic.

Page Edit History:
  • HerpVolunteer 01/22/2014 01:55 PM

1 962

Started for Los Angeles at 10:30. Did a little shopping first. An uneventful trip. Lunched at Stan's Drive in at Wilshired and Hoover. Then to the Parkway Motel arriving at almost 1:30.

Dr Russell called a few minutes later and came over to visit. Stayed almost an hour. We talked all kinds of herp. problems, his coming trip to Cambridge, England; what he will do there etc. He has with him Richard Scharfinberger, a bibliographer who is making a very large bibliography of snake venom, and who will come to SD some time to check my material, particularly looking at Bull AVIA and other obscene stems, looking especially for secondary bibs. There was also Terry Davidson, a high school student, and Fred Buess. Russell told me of the unexpectedly high toxicites of the venoms of C scitulatus and C. mitchellix mitchelli which compare with tigris venom.

We had supper at Carl's and then went to the Shrine Auditorium
(Continued in June (28)

1 962

First thing this morning I took the Cad to a nearby Standard Station to have the brakes examined. Luckily and unexpectedly there was a mechanic available (he was asleep in his car in the garage). He made an examination and found a bloom oil seal on the right rear whell. Said at would take 1 1/2 days to fix. Could make it to San Diego but not to go over 40 and use brake as little as possible. So we started out at 9:30 and arrived at 12:10. There was much traffic and it was a rather uncomfortable drive. I stayed in the right lane and held the speed down. Only had to apply the brakes 3 or 4 times on the entire trip.

Spent the afternoon resting and unpacking.

Went out to Les's with Phil at 3:30 and worked until 5:30. Filled all the barrels. Tied up plenty newspapers, all the rubbish was will take.

1962

At the office this morning.

Today I made real progress on the AK biography, especially in organizing the arrangements and making some of the final additions and insertions as called for by the miscellaneous notes accumulated during the last several months.

I find that in the organization into logical sequence of material of this character, a process at which I was once pretty good, I am now much handicapped by a deterioration of memory. I can't even remember whether certain parts have or have not been included, or where, which makes it increasingly difficult.

Amy Lamberton and Lucy Bell in for dinner tonight. The Millers came later.

1 962

Had a bad attack of cystitis beginning about midnight last night. Quite uncomfortable.

Tried to get Fishburn all day, at his residence, office and call agency. No luck.

Finally called Prentiss. He was out but his wife had Howe call me. Got a sulfa prescription at 3:20 that eased things considerably.

Steve Arnold called but I was too uncomfortable to see him.

I had expected to get back on the AK biography today, and had left all material out on my desk. But I was too lousy and put it all away.

Fishburn called late this afternoon. He had been fishing in Lowes California.

1 962

Feeling better today but not much pep or strength.

Went out to Less' this afternoon for a few minutes. The trash men had removed all rubbish set out last Saturday.

Picked up several cartons of letters and such like and brought them home for survey to see that nothing of value was destroyed. This proved to be a waste of time. The material was all worthless junk.

Man called me this morning from Los Angeles (I think) to consult about his son who was in a Palm Spring's hospital under treatment for sidewinder bite. Son (17) was bitten reaching in a bush for a lizard; didn't see the sidewinder until he was bitten. L A Co. hospital suggested he call me as Russell was on his way to England. His doctor Artken had given 2 doses of antivenin. I couldn't offer much except encouragement.

1 962

At the office this morning. Up to Dr. Gerald Howe's Office at 10:45. Had a pyelogram and a cystoscopic examination. Altogether, including the x-rays, with waits between it took almost 1.5 hours. Despite the use of a local anesthetic it was moderately painful and left some stinging after-effects. As nearly as I could understand Howes conclusion there are parts of the prostate still left which form a sort of iris and a continued obstruction. This tends to result in repeated infections. He intimated they ought to be removed. Howe is going to consult Mullenix and Prentiss and report their combined conclusions next Wednesday. I doubt whether I would go for an operation since the conditions antedating the original removal of the prostate required something drastic; I simply could not go on as I was then. He said they found no sign of cancer.

1 962

At the office for awhile this morning.

Worked up one item for the Cyclo Americana article.

Had an appointment with Dr. Howe at 11:30, but he was in surgery so I saw Dr. Prentiss. The nurse thought I was to have some more tests but Prentiss said no - last weeks were sufficient and he didn't want to cause any more irritation. The red stuff I have been taking he referred to as iso-gantricin. This I should now discontinue, but he said I would do well to keep some in reserve (which I already have) and use it in case of a recurrence of infection. Meanwhile he gave me a new prescription which I am to take for the next 6 weeks and then report for a checkup. He called it gantricin but Whelen referred to it as one of the sulfas. The reappointment should be with Howe again.

Prentiss said there were some new nodules in the prostate capsule

(Continued on July 31)

(Friday, Sept. 7, Continued)

I think it was the largest crowd I had ever seen at one of these breakfasts, so the postponement until after Labor Day hadn't interfered with the attendance.

The President of the State Fair introduced the head-table guests which took 5 minutes and then talked for 4 minutes on the plans for the new state fair buildings and grounds. The Governor Pat Brown talked about the State's economy for 17 minutes; he didn't belittle the great success of his administration. Fortunately for us he had to leave early for another engagement. Then Bob Hurnlay president

Worked on intermedius, and omiltemanus, made a new map and got a better territorial view. The AMNH specimens will be important with respect to the validity of gloydi. They were taken nearer the type locality of gloydi then was the David-Dixon specimen.

An inquiry elicited the information that the new and not the retiring directors would be present at the meeting of the Board on Friday. We elected the officers for the coming year and adjourned.

From 9:30 to 11:50 I presided at the Natural Resources in the absence of Bob Sproul who is in Australia. With the help of the committee secretary Larry Kiml, I got through OK. although all the speakers and most of the audience were strangers to me. The program was

1) "Plans for the Development of Fish and Game Resources" Walter Shannon, Director State Department of Fish and Game.

2) "The Outlook for Wilderness and Other Land-Use Restrictions in California'' Myron Kreuger, Prof Emeritus. U.C.

(Continued on November 18)

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 01/28/2014 07:05 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 01:05 PM

1 962

I spent most of the morning writing up a memorandum of my two meetings with the Press people on Tuesday and Wednesday. This was a considerable chore and took over 2 hours.

At noon I went out via taxi and had lunch with Dorie Coblentz, cracked crab and artichoke. After discussing family affairs for awhile we visited the new Happy Valley Branch Library, a really fine plant, larger and more expensive plant than we can afford at home. But of course their population is more concentrated. I got some data from the librarian in charge. We then had to return to Dorie's for my brief case, which I had forgotten. I then returned to the hotel and made up a package of laundry etc. to mail home, partly to save weight and partly to avoid having the suit case bust and scatter my goods all over Market Street. Mailed this at the Bush St. P.O., not too far away.

(Continued on November 12)

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 01/28/2014 07:12 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 01:05 PM

1962

This morning I went over and made further corrections in the Press memorandum.

Went out and bought a last Sunday's New York Times and then out to the Academy where I arrived at 10:30. Met AL Leviton, Benny Banta and Wilmer Tanner. We discussed a lot of herpetological problems until 12, when we continued the discussion at lunch until 1:00, when Benny and Wilmer drove me down to the Palace.

Al Larton believes that his results in the analysis of venom and blood samples by electrophoresis is showing a lot of relationships conclusively, consistently, and accurately that will change and settle many taxonomic problems. He finds that viridis is not closely related to oreganus or helleri. I forget where lutosus fits in. There are many other relationships and absence of relationships that he claims to have proven that will change taxonomy extensively, but unfortunately

(Continued on Nov. 22)

1962

Took my driver's license test this morning from 8:45 to 10. It was quite a chore.

I did OK on the No. 3 Questions and Answers (100%) but I barely passed the driving test - 72 out of 100, with a necessary score of 70. The guy penalized me 16 on not looking back on lane changes (using the mirror evidently doesn't count; missing a sign/traffic signal (I don't where that was) cost me 6 points; and poor backing into a parking space 6 points. I couldn't see the thin vertical pipes clear enough to do a job with the long Cad.

At the office from 10:15 until noon. Had a long conference with Hi Dillin on the Pendleton atomic plant and the proposed California back-bone transmission line.

Went to the Gas Co Women's Dinner Party tonight. The dinner was OK but the entertainment a little on the dull side. Pretty tired from the test this morning.

1 962

Today I started to line up work on the bibliography for the second printing, first selecting the pink sheets to be included and those to be omitted from the supplement. Also planned a method for indexing the bibliographic references by subject.

I find that bibliographic work is less onerous for me than any other work on second printing. I have a real interest and liking for bibliographic work. So I made some progress today.

At the office this morning.

Worked on the supplemental bibliography today. Started to copy the entries from the pink sheets, first for Miss Molloy and later for the Press. This is going to be a slow, repetitive and time-consuming job, but it is advisable to do it at once, in my interest of safety, considering my age. It will be an important part of the supplement, and no one else can do it.

1 962

At the office this morning.

Carded separates; worked a little on bibliography.

Had a two hour session of the Executive Committee this morning to discuss possible gas rebates because of recent Federal Power Commission Decision.

Receive from the University Press today four cases containing all the cuts (halftone and line) that were used to print Rattlesnakes (since the crucial meeting with the Press representatives on Sept. 10) has gone much slower than I expected. The grave question is Will I last to complete what I have undertaken. My efficiency is at a low ebb; the amount of work I can do in a day is very disappointing and disconcerting.
